ape. Using the metaphor of the kaleidoscope, with each turn of the wheel, another aspect of the city is materialised. In doing so, the contributors complicate the dominant narrative of Manchester’s renaissance as driven by the city administration’s entrepreneurial ethos. By taking up civic space and resources with council-led cultural representations focused largely on generating financial income for the city, three decades of command-and-control politics has inhibited grassroots and spontaneous forms of emergent publics.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aCities and townszEnglandzManchester. 0aEthnologyzEnglandzManchester. 0aSociology, UrbanzEnglandzManchester. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Public Policy / City Planning & Urban Development.2bisacsh  aManchester's urban challenges.  abirth rituals.  acarbon emissions.  acivic actors.  acivic parade.  acommunity groups.  adeath rituals.  aentrepreneurial' governance.  aethnographic analyses.  aglobalisation.  alocal communities.  aloungification.  amigration.  aorganisational structures.  aurban ethnographers.  aurban policy.  aurban spaces.1 aAtkins, Michael, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKnox, Hannah, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLang, Luciana, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLewis, Camilla, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLewis, Camilla, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aO’Doherty, Damian, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPieri, Elisa, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPoulton, George, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSmith, Katherine, econtributor.4ctb